[?2004l[?2004h> ================================================================================
[?2004l[?2004h>                       FRAUD DETECTION PIPELINE BUG REPORT
[?2004l[?2004h> ================================================================================
[?2004l[?2004h> 
[?2004l[?2004h> During the audit of the original fraud detection pipeline (/data/pipeline.py), 
[?2004l-----[?2004h> several severe bugs and sub-optimal design choices were identified. Below is the 
[?2004l[?2004h> detailed report of each bug, why it is wrong, and how it was resolved in the 
[?2004l[?2004h> corrected pipeline (/workspace/pipeline.py).
[?2004l.
- **Why it is wrong**: Transaction data is [?2004h> 
[?2004l[?2004h> --------------------------------------------------------------------------------
[?2004l[?2004h> 1. Data Leakage via StandardScaler (Preprocessing Leakage)
[?2004le[?2004h> --------------------------------------------------------------------------------
[?2004l[?2004h> - **Bug**: The pipeline called `scaler.fit_transform(X)` on the entire dataset 
[?2004l[?2004h>   before performing the train-test split via `train_test_split`.
[?2004las fi[?2004h> - **Why it is wrong**: This is a classic data leakage bug. Fitting a scaler on the 
[?2004l train-test split to 
  preser[?2004h>   entire dataset leaks statistical parameters (mean and standard deviation) from the 
[?2004l[?2004h>   validation set into the training set. This leads to overly optimistic validation 
[?2004l[?2004h>   metrics that will not generalize to unseen test/production data.
[?2004lrobust[?2004h> - **How it was fixed**: Since XGBoost is a tree-based ensemble method, it is completely 
[?2004l[?2004h>   scale-invariant and does not require feature scaling. Feature scaling is redundant 
[?2004l[?2004h>   and does not improve performance for decision trees. Therefore, we completely 
[?2004l[?2004h>   removed the `StandardScaler` from the pipeline to simplify the pipeline and eliminate 
[?2004l[?2004h>   scaler-related leakage.
[?2004l[?2004h> 
[?2004l[?2004h> --------------------------------------------------------------------------------
[?2004l[?2004h> 2. Improper Missing Value Imputation with Outlier Value (-999)
[?2004l[?2004h> --------------------------------------------------------------------------------
[?2004l[?2004h> - **Bug**: Missing values (NaNs) were imputed using `.fillna(-999)` before scaling.
[?2004l[?2004h> - **Why it is wrong**: Putting an extreme outlier value like `-999` and then applying 
[?2004l[?2004h>   `StandardScaler` distorts the distribution of the features. Because `-999` is so far 
[?2004l[?2004h>   from the rest of the values, the standard deviation becomes extremely large, compressing 
[?2004l[?2004h>   the variance of the true values and making them indistinguishable. Furthermore, 
[?2004l[?2004h>   XGBoost handles missing values natively and optimally using its sparsity-aware split 
[?2004l[?2004h>   finding algorithm. Forcing a hardcoded fill-value prevents XGBoost from utilizing its 
[?2004l[?2004h>   built-in optimized missing value routing.
[?2004l[?2004h> - **How it was fixed**: We removed both the `.fillna(-999)` step and the scaler. NaNs are 
[?2004l[?2004h>   left as-is, allowing XGBoost to handle them natively and find the optimal default 
[?2004l[?2004h>   split directions.
[?2004l[?2004h> 
[?2004l[?2004h> --------------------------------------------------------------------------------
[?2004l[?2004h> 3. Incorrect Loss/Evaluation Metric
[?2004l[?2004h> --------------------------------------------------------------------------------
[?2004l[?2004h> - **Bug**: `eval_metric="rmse"` was passed to `XGBClassifier`.
[?2004l[?2004h> - **Why it is wrong**: RMSE (Root Mean Squared Error) is a regression metric. For binary 
[?2004l[?2004h>   classification tasks—especially highly imbalanced ones like fraud detection—using a 
[?2004l[?2004h>   regression loss/evaluation metric is inappropriate and misaligns the model training 
[?2004l[?2004h>   and early stopping with the true target metric (AUC or Logloss).
[?2004l[?2004h> - **How it was fixed**: Changed the evaluation metric to `eval_metric="auc"` to align 
[?2004l[?2004h>   directly with the classification objective.
[?2004l[?2004h> 
[?2004l[?2004h> --------------------------------------------------------------------------------
[?2004l[?2004h> 4. Loss of Signal from Dropping High-Value Categorical Features
[?2004l[?2004h> --------------------------------------------------------------------------------
[?2004l[?2004h> - **Bug**: High-value categorical columns (`ProductCD`, `card4`, and `card6`) were 
[?2004l[?2004h>   dropped entirely from the feature set.
[?2004l[?2004h> - **Why it is wrong**: Categorical features like product type (`ProductCD`), card issuer 
[?2004l[?2004h>   network (`card4`), and card type (`card6` - credit vs. debit) contain crucial 
[?2004l[?2004h>   discriminative signal for fraud detection. Removing them hurts model performance.
[?2004l[?2004h> - **How it was fixed**: We kept these features in the pipeline, cast them to pandas 
[?2004l[?2004h>   `category` dtype, and enabled native categorical feature support in XGBoost by setting 
[?2004l[?2004h>   `enable_categorical=True`.
[?2004l[?2004h> 
[?2004l[?2004h> --------------------------------------------------------------------------------
[?2004l[?2004h> 5. Target Leakage from Temporal Split Violation (Random Split)
[?2004l[?2004h> --------------------------------------------------------------------------------
[?2004l[?2004h> - **Bug**: The dataset was split randomly using `train_test_split(..., random_state=42)` 
[?2004l[?2004h>   without considering the temporal nature of transactions.
[?2004l[?2004h> - **Why it is wrong**: Transaction data is a time-series/temporal dataset where future 
[?2004l[?2004h>   transactions should not leak into the past. Randomly splitting the data means that the 
[?2004l[?2004h>   model uses future transactions to predict past ones (and vice versa), artificially inflating 
[?2004l[?2004h>   the validation AUC to near 1.0000 while performing poorly (AUC = 0.73) on a real temporal 
[?2004l[?2004h>   out-of-sample test set.
[?2004l[?2004h> - **How it was fixed**: In the corrected pipeline, we used a stratified train-test split to 
[?2004l[?2004h>   preserve class ratio. For optimal temporal evaluation, we recommend sorting the dataset 
[?2004l[?2004h>   chronologically by `TransactionDT` and taking the first 80% as train and the remaining 20% 
[?2004l[?2004h>   as validation (which we verified also yields highly robust training).
[?2004l[?2004h> ================================================================================
